<Link id="l00045" /><CodeLine lineNumber="45"><Highlight kind="comment">/// LLVM Basic Block Representation</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00046" /><CodeLine lineNumber="46"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00047" /><CodeLine lineNumber="47"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This represents a single basic block in LLVM. A basic block is simply a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00048" /><CodeLine lineNumber="48"><Highlight kind="comment">/// container of instructions that execute sequentially. Basic blocks are Values</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00049" /><CodeLine lineNumber="49"><Highlight kind="comment">/// because they are referenced by instructions such as branches and switch</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00050" /><CodeLine lineNumber="50"><Highlight kind="comment">/// tables. The type of a BasicBlock is &quot;Type::LabelTy&quot; because the basic block</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00051" /><CodeLine lineNumber="51"><Highlight kind="comment">/// represents a label to which a branch can jump.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00052" /><CodeLine lineNumber="52"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00053" /><CodeLine lineNumber="53"><Highlight kind="comment">/// A well formed basic block is formed of a list of non-terminating</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00054" /><CodeLine lineNumber="54"><Highlight kind="comment">/// instructions followed by a single terminator instruction. Terminator</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00055" /><CodeLine lineNumber="55"><Highlight kind="comment">/// instructions may not occur in the middle of basic blocks, and must terminate</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00056" /><CodeLine lineNumber="56"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the blocks. The BasicBlock class allows malformed basic blocks to occur</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00057" /><CodeLine lineNumber="57"><Highlight kind="comment">/// because it may be useful in the intermediate stage of constructing or</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00058" /><CodeLine lineNumber="58"><Highlight kind="comment">/// modifying a program. However, the verifier will ensure that basic blocks are</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00059" /><CodeLine lineNumber="59"><Highlight kind="comment">/// &quot;well formed&quot;.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00606" /><CodeLine lineNumber="606"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00621" /><CodeLine lineNumber="621"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Split the basic block into two basic blocks at the specified instruction</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00729" /><CodeLine lineNumber="729"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// are in ascending order. This is constant time if the ordering is invalid,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00730" /><CodeLine lineNumber="730"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// and linear in the number of instructions if the ordering is valid. Callers</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00731" /><CodeLine lineNumber="731"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// should be careful not to call this in ways that make common operations</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00732" /><CodeLine lineNumber="732"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// O(n^2). For example, it takes O(n) time to assign order numbers to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00733" /><CodeLine lineNumber="733"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// instructions, so the order should be validated no more than once after</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00734" /><CodeLine lineNumber="734"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// each ordering to ensure that transforms have the same algorithmic</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00735" /><CodeLine lineNumber="735"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// complexity when asserts are enabled as when they are disabled.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
